Spectrometers and Demultiplexer

 Range of 242–800 nm, excepting 335–385, 465–510 nm

 Resolutions of 0.2 nm FWHM below 500 nm, 0.65 nm FWHM above 500 nm

 Wavelength drift <5 nm over the course of the mission

 Demultiplexer transmission efficiency ≥50 % to each spectrometer channel

 Spectrometer Transmission x detector quantum efficiency ≥0.31 %

 Dark current levels at 10 s exposure of <25 % of pixel full well level at 20 ∘C

 Pixel rows binned on-chip adjustable 1–256, separately adjustable, each spectrometer

 Integration times adjustable from 10 ms to 30 s in <5 ms increments

 Exposure synchronization with laser to within 50 μs

 Acquisition of data at rates up to 10 Hz, for up to 150 spectra

 Capable of 2D images for diagnostic purposes

Calibration Target

 Contain at least one sample representing each of the major expected rock types

 Each target to have an angular extent ≥10 mrad as viewed from mast unit

 Each target shall be able to accommodate 100 analyses of 75 laser pulses each

 Assembly to incorporate an RMI geometric calibration feature

Baseline spectral measurements (B(λ)) of the test system were taken to record the nominal response of the system without a test fiber. The PMT voltage, integration time and number of co-added samples were varied over selected spectral ranges to account for spectral variations in the light source, PMT responsivity, spectral characteristics of the order sorting filters, and system throughput efficiency. These parameters were programmed into the monochromator scanning software to keep the signal from saturating the PMT at any point in the spectrum and to boost the signal in low-response regions of the spectrum. Dark scans (D(λ)) of the experimental apparatus were then taken with the light source switched off to record the spectral effects observed from incident room light and dark current from the PMT. Finally, signal scans were taken (S(λ)) with the fiber under test inserted between the integrating sphere and the fiber connecting to the monochromator to measure its spectral insertion loss. The spectral throughput of the fiber (T(λ)) was then calculated from these three data sets according to the equation \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$T(\lambda) = \frac{S(\lambda ) - D(\lambda )}{B(\lambda ) - D(\lambda )} $$\end{document} The results led us to select the standard high-OH multimode 0.22 NA fiber (Polymicro FVA 300330500) along with a standard W.L. Gore FON 1442 1.4 mm diameter tight-wrapped jacket. This jacket combination consists of a thin buffer layer of ePTFE, a J800 fluoropolymer protective layer, a bradded Kevlar layer for strength, and a final outer J800 fluoropolymer layer. Prior to termination, the jacketed fiber was preconditioned with 40 thermal cycles ranging from −30 ∘C to +110 ∘C. Both ends of the fiber were terminated with Diamond AVIM 6236.6 flight-qualified connectors.

The optical response of the VIO and VNIR spectrometers were determined using a calibrated Labsphere integrating sphere and lamp assembly. This standard provided spatially uniform radiance, generally on the 2 % or better level, across its ∼100 mm aperture and over angles up to 9.5∘. For these measurements the ChemCam telescope was focused on the aperture plane or a few centimeters in front of it. Uniformity of the back surface sufficient for the expanding angle through focus was verified with both lateral and longitudinal displacements of the sphere, and no changes in sensor output beyond sensor noise levels were noted. Given the large source area and ChemCam’s small field of view, constant radiance is provided for all relevant viewing distances for ChemCam. The system response in digital numbers (DN) can be written as: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathit{DN} = L\cdot A\cdot \varOmega \cdot \Delta\lambda \cdot \Delta t \cdot t_{0}\cdot \sigma + \mathit{DN}_{0} $$\end{document} where L is the source radiance in photons/second/cm2/sr/μm wavelength, A is the source area imaged, in cm2, Ω is the solid viewing angle in sr, Δλ is the detector wavelength bin width in μm, Δt is the integration time in seconds, t0 is the system throughput multiplied by the detector quantum efficiency, in electrons per photon, σ is the amplified conversion gain in DN/electron, and DN0 is the offset due to stray light and electrical offsets from zero DN. The last term can be removed by subtracting a spectrum obtained with the radiance source turned off. All measurements are made with the room lights off. The equation can then be solved for the product of t0⋅σ, giving the optical response for each spectral bin in photons per DN.

The UV spectral range had to be calibrated in a slightly different way due to the lack of an integrating sphere standard irradiance source in that wavelength range. A fiber-receptacle irradiance standard was used to characterize the UV range from a flight spare FOC through the spectrometer, and the telescope transmission was measured separately: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathit{DN} = I_{\lambda}\cdot A\cdot\Delta\lambda \cdot\Delta\cdot t\cdot t_{\mathrm{tel}}\cdot t_{\mathrm{back}}\cdot\sigma + \mathit{DN}_{0} $$\end{document} where Iλ is the reference source irradiance in photons/second/cm2/μm wavelength, A is the area of the fiber tip being illuminated, in cm2, ttel is the telescope throughput, and tback is the back-end throughput multiplied by detector quantum efficiency. The product ttel⋅tback is equivalent to t0 above. The telescope throughput ttel was obtained via measurements where the FOC directly viewed a small integrating sphere illuminated by a large UV source. This measurement was subsequently compared with the spectrometer output when the fiber was illuminated by the telescope image of the sphere radiance.
